<p>A young Jewish man in Moscow, hoping to go along to get along, did his best to act the part of the good Communist. However, he just couldn't wrap his head around some of the ideology. Finally, he discreetly consulted his rabbi to see if he cold clarify the notion of "dialectical materialism".</p>
<p>The rabbi said, "I will illustrate with a parable. Moshe and Aaron climb down a chimney. Moshe is covered with soot, but Aaron somehow manages to keep himself clean. Which of them washes himself?"</p>
<p>"Moshe, of course!"</p>
<p>The rabbi shook his head. "No -- Aaron washes himself. He sees Moshe standing in front of him dirty, and assumes that he must have gotten dirty, while Moshe sees Aaron standing in front of him clean, and assumes that he must also be clean. Now... Moshe and Aaron climb down a chimney. Moshe is covered with soot, but Aaron somehow manages to keep himself clean. Which of them washes himself?"</p>
<p>"That's the same question you just asked! Aaron washes himself.</p>
